Remote Development on Raspberry= Pi with VS Code

=09

Note: This requires VS Code Inside= rs.


21/01/2020 Update: Remote development for = ARM processors such as the Raspberry Pi are now supported on VS Code, and V= S Code Insiders is no longer a requirement.

As much as I love the Raspberry Pi, I found developing code on it to be = uncomfortable and sometimes cumbersome. Some great IDEs like Atom don=E2=80= =99t support ARM processors so can=E2=80=99t be used on the raspberry Pi wh= ereas others like Thonny are very basic (in my opinion). Also, the RPi migh= t not powerful enough to run heavy IDEs smoothly.

Remote development solves all this by allowing you to develop your code = on your favourite device such as your laptop but run it externally on a hos= t (like the RPi). Apart from getting all the niceties your laptop=E2=80=99s= coding environment offers, it can also be faster to code and debug due to = your laptop=E2=80=99s compute power compared to any Raspberry Pi=E2=80=99s.=

As a quick side note, alternatives to remote development on VS code I= nsiders include:

  • Pycharm Pro: The pro version has integrated remote development supp= ort.
  • PuTTY and FileZilla: using SSH via PuTTY to run code that you = develop on a PC and transferred to the RPi beforehand using FileZilla.

Step 1: Ensuring you = can SSH into your host without entering a password

For remote development to work in VS Code Insiders, you need to a= ble to SSH into your RPi without entering your credentials every time. If y= ou need to set this up, please read my article on Password-less SSH into Raspberry Pi with openSSH. You know= you=E2=80=99ve got this working when you can simply run ssh pi@IP_AD= DRESS (where IP_ADDRESS is the IP address of your RPi) in a command = prompt (windows) / terminal and your SSH-ed into your RPi straightaway with= out entering any credentials.

Step 2: Install Visual studio code Insiders and extensions

You can download and install the latest version of VS Code Insiders here (Update: or you ca= n download latest version of VS Code here). We=E2=80=99ll then need to install the Remote Development extension from the exte= nsions section:

The remote development extension contains the remote-ssh extension which= we will now uninstall (simply disabling it isn=E2=80=99t enough), as we wa= nt to use Remote =E2=80=93 SSH (Nightly) ins= tead which supports ARM processors like the Raspberry Pi=E2=80=99s.

21/01/2020 Update: Don=E2=80=99t uninstall= Remote-SSH extension if your using VS Code instead of VS Code Insiders. Re= mote-SSH now supports the Raspberry Pi.
